Description


Apartments 5 and 6 are our newest residence halls. They are providing suite-style living for approximately 150 male and female students (per building) in separate suites. These apartments are open to all upper-class students. Most suites contain four single bedrooms, two full bathrooms, and a common living area with furniture, a built-in flat screen television, and a full-size refrigerator. Each suite contains a common access closet off the living room for bikes and other storage. Each building has laundry facilities on the second floor and elevator access. There are four Resident Assistants per building (one on each floor). RA's can be found each evening in the common area on the first floor.



More Information


  • A courtyard between the two buildings was created as an outdoor gathering and grilling space for students to congregate and cook. Gathering spaces also represent the college’s commitment to engaged learning through visually accessible but acoustically separate study areas. A lecture area was also integrated into one of the buildings and is currently being used for classes as well as student activities.


  • Apartments

    Apt 5-6 Single room approximately 10.5’ x 13’

    Apartment 5 features campus community space in the form of a large lounge area that includes a gaming television/play area, a fitness center, an arcade gaming area, a large saltwater aquarium, and state-of-the-art energy pods in our Relaxation Room.

    Common Room Overview: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GBQYV4FquX0


  • Gameroom

    Foosball

    Racing

    Pinball (Ghostbusters and Star Wars)

    Pool

    Air Hockey


  • E-sports Arena

    Saint Leo University offers an Esports Arena, where students compete, broadcast, and watch their favorite Esports games. It is a school-sponsored competitive team in League of Legends, Valorant, Overwatch, FIFA, Super Smash Brothers. APEX Legends, Fortnite, Rocket League, and Dragon Ball Z. The varsity and junior varsity teams compete with other local, regional, and national universities throughout the year.


  • Residence Life

    The Saint Leo University Office of Residence Life (RES Life) empowers students to develop a safe and inclusive living experience that promotes a thriving community of holistic student learning. RES Life is here to help students with all of their housing-related needs; from room changes to helping students who get locked out of their rooms, they can help with anything and everything.

    Hours

    Monday - Friday: 8am - 5pm

    Saturday - Sunday: Closed

    Contact Information

    (352) 588-8268 or residence.life@saintleo.edu

Description


Marmion Hall houses over 110 first-year men and Snyder Hall houses over 140 first-year women in a traditional "community style" layout. The buildings are known as the first-year residence hall and are most often referred to as "Marmion/Snyder" because the two buildings are physically connected by a lobby area on the first floor - sharing the Lion's Den, a large game, fitness, and study lounge area.



More Information


  • There are three floors in Marmion Hall and four floors in Snyder Hall with a Resident Assistant (RA) assigned to each floor. RAs sit at the front desk located in the main lobby each night, and residents can enter the building through the parking lot lobby entrance or the back entrance of the Lion's Den (facing the main campus). Vending machines are also available in the lobby area. The Marmion laundry room is located on the first floor and the Snyder laundry room is located on the garden level.


  • Marmion Double is 16' x 11'

    Snyder Double is 14'x 11'


  • “ When I was a freshman here I actually chose to live in Snyder over Henderson because the dorms here are bigger width-wise, and I wanted more space. This is where I had my first college experience and it helped me grow, even though we were more “secluded” than the rest of campus it creates a tight-knit community. I’ve made friendships here that have lasted my entire college experience.” Emmalee Welch, Senior. RA at Snyder/Marmion

Description


Henderson Hall houses over 180 first-year women in a traditional "community style" layout. There are three floors separated into two wings with a Resident Assistant (RA) assigned and communal bathrooms in each wing. Rooms also feature a built-in vanity (counter, sink, and cabinets). In the building, the laundry room is located on the third floor and the game room and study lounge is located on the first floor. An outdoor sand volleyball court is located between Henderson Hall and Benoit Hall which is used year round by east side residents.



Dimensions


  • Henderson is 18' x 10'

Description


Benoit Hall houses over 120 first-year male residents in a traditional "community style" layout. There are two floors separated into two wings with a Resident Assistant (RA) assigned and communal bathrooms in each wing. Rooms also feature a built-in vanity (counter, sink, and cabinets). Adjacent to Benoit is an outdoor sand volleyball court, which can be used year-round and is shared with other east-side residents. Benoit's laundry room and lounge are both located on the first floor.

  • Benoit is 18' x 10'

Description


The University Safety Department seriously provide a safe and secure environment for our students, faculty, staff, and visitors. They are staffed with trained and professional officers who are certified in their field by the State of Florida. They patrol the campus twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week, on foot, mountain bikes, patrol car, and golf carts.

Contact: (352) 588-8432

Emergency only: (352) 588-8333

Saint Leo University has an extremely low crime rate and we believe that you will find our University Safety personnel to be friendly, caring, and attentive to your concerns.


Services


  • ID Parking Decal

    All students, staff, and faculty members at Saint Leo University must have an ID parking decal so that they can park on campus. This helps keep unauthorized people off campus.


  • Safe rides

    Saint Leo University has a student-run Safe Rides program. It’s an escort service for students who need to get to the other side of campus. This service is available all hours and is a convenient option for those who might not feel comfortable walking alone at night.


  • ADA Accessibility Transportation

    The campus security team gives transportation for people with disabilities who require assistance getting around campus. This service is an important resource for members of the campus community with mobility issues.


  • Motor Pool

    Students can rent vans from the motor pool at a rate of 45 cents per mile. This is an option for student groups who need a vehicle for off-campus events or activities.


  • 24/7 Patrol

    The security team is on patrol 24/7 and can respond to incidents as needed. This constant patrol helps make sure that students, staff, and visitors feel safe on campus.


  • BAWA Program

    The BAWA program was made to connect victims of sexual assault, domestic violence, and/or stalking to resources such as counseling, Title IX services, and off-campus resources. This program is a critical resource for the people of the campus community who may be experiencing these types of issues.

Description


It is currently the main office space for many faculty and staff members, began its construction in 1926. However, at that time of the year, the hall was once to be designed as a dormitory – the first ever at the school – for students. Each of the offices used to be a living space for students, and many offices were once used for other purposes such as a shower, a library, or a reception room. In 1940, loudspeakers were placed above the building and were used to broadcast the new campus radio station WLEO.



Services


  • Financial aid office

    Student financial aid is the office located directly in the center of Saint Edward’s Hall. They assist students in navigating the process of applying for scholarships, grants, loans, and other financial assistance to help fund their education. Here at the Financial aid office can go by appointment to take care of all their finical concerns and needs such as:

    Checking student accounts

    Add to or take away from their financial aid on their student accounts

    Hours

    Monday- Friday: 8:30 am - 5:00 pm


  • Student Accounts/Billing

    This office handles tuition and fee payments, issues student bills, and manages other financial matters related to student accounts.


  • Center of Learning and Excellence (CTLE)

    To help the faculty be the most successful teacher they can be so that they can help the students to be the most successful students they can be. We do all sorts of things like webinars, workshops, and Faculty Development. We provide a ton of resources on the website. Faculty can consult with us in one-on-one consultation about any kind of teaching challenges, issues, strategies that they want to try out, and navigating tools.

    Website: http://faculty.saintleo.edu

  • Advisor’s Offices

    Need to stop by your advisor’s office to attend their office hours? Advisor's offices/adjuncts (full-time faculty advisors) are the main function of this house's faculty offices.

  • Registrar's Office

    The Registrar maintains the official academic record for all students; located at the far west end of Saint Edward Hall.. The team specifically works with transcripts from other schools, transfer credit evaluation, degree audits, substitution/waiver requests, enrollment verifications, degree conferral, issuing diplomas, degree verifications, transcripts, enrollment reporting, commencement, centralized tuition assistance management, and many other tasks associated with these functions. Our work impacts and supports all departments across the university. Students most often contact the Registrar’s Office for transcripts, transfer evaluations, degree conferral, and verifications. In short, It is an office designed all around to help you transition into Saint Leo and out the easiest and best ways possible.

    Hours

    Monday - Friday: 8 am - 5 pm

Description


The Military Resource Center (MRC) is a place on campus for veterans and other military-connected students to unwind and receive information that may be relevant for a future job or VA benefits. The building serves as a gathering place where student-veterans, active-duty, and reserve service members, and ROTC cadets can relax, study, meet with advisers, and receive help from external support centers.



Services


  • There are a variety of audiences for the MRC like incoming student veterans, current military-connected students (spouses, dependents, etc.), parents of military-connected students, and more. When military members separate or retire from service, they may feel out of their element or disconnected from society; however, the MRC has an environment that mimics one a veteran might see in the military.


  • Can be helpful with general questions about VA benefits ( Post 9/11 GI Bill, disability claims, etc.).


  • Hosts military-themed events for all students, staff, and faculty.

  • Offers networking opportunities.

  • Presents a friendly, tight-knit environment for all military-connected students similar to the environment in the military.

  • Contact Info

    military.services@saintleo.edu or call (352) 588-8853.

Description


The Student Activities Building (SAB) is a vibrant hub that fosters a sense of community and engagement among students. This versatile space serves as a center for various extracurricular activities, events, and student gatherings. With its modern amenities and flexible layout, the Student Activity Building accommodates a diverse range of functions, from club meetings and workshops to social events and performances.

Description


The Student Community Center (SCC) is a vibrant hub of campus life, fostering a sense of belonging and providing students with many opportunities for engagement and growth. It is a central gathering place where students from diverse backgrounds come together to connect, collaborate, and build lasting friendships. The center features modern facilities, including versatile event spaces, recreational areas, and comfortable lounges, all designed to accommodate the various needs and interests of the student body. From hosting club meetings and cultural events to offering spaces for relaxation and study, the area enriches the Saint Leo University experience, creating a lively and inclusive atmosphere that enhances personal and academic development.


Services


  • Stephen Herrmann Mail Center

    The Stephen Herrmann Mail Center handles all the incoming and outgoing mail for the University and its student residents. All residential students are assigned a mail code in which your package is sorted and then placed in an available locker to be picked up. Alternatively, if items do not fit in the lockers, they will be available for pickup at the customer service window during hours of operation.

    An email notification will be sent to your Saint Leo email account for each package after it has been scanned into our system and is available for pickup. You must enter your pin/scan your barcode at the lockers. Mail and packages will only be available for pickup in the lockers for 72 hours, after that time you will need to see an associate at the customer service window to receive your item(s). You must use a Saint Leo student ID at the customer service window to receive your items. All mail or packages must be claimed within 10 business days.

    The MC (mail code) is your specific number for each of your academic years. Please note that all mail and packages need to have your name and mail code on them. Any items that do not have this information will experience a delay in delivery as faculty works to identify the correct recipient. If you happen to use your old code from your previous year after a new code is assigned, you will still be able to be identified using your name.

    Below is some important information regarding the mail center and addresses to keep in handy depending on which mail service you use or receive from.

  • Bookstore

    The Bookstore at Saint Leo University is a vital hub for students, faculty, and the campus community, providing essential resources and a welcoming environment. As you step into the store, you'll find a comprehensive collection of course materials, textbooks, and academic supplies meticulously curated to support the diverse array of programs and disciplines offered at the University.

    Saint Leo partnered with Barnes & Noble College to offer an easy-to-use and convenient process for ordering course materials. The Bookstore often hosts special events, promotions, and sales to discover new items. Beyond textbooks, the bookstore offers a rich selection of merchandise, including spirited Saint Leo apparel, accessories, and gifts that allow individuals to proudly showcase their collegiate pride. From stylish clothing to branded mementos, the store offers a range of options to celebrate the school's identity and foster a sense of belonging.

    The staff at the Bookstore is always ready to assist, whether by helping students locate the required materials for their courses or guiding them through the latest selections of Saint Leo gear. Their dedication to service ensures that everyone has a positive experience and finds what they need.

    19 Meal Plan

    With this plan, you receive any 19 meals per week. This meal plan operates on a Sunday through Saturday weekly schedule. Meals that are not utilized for that week do not carry over to the following week. Only you can obtain a meal with your meal card. Meals cannot be shared. With this plan, you can take advantage of free equivalency meals at FUZ Fusion Eatery also called “Penny Meal”, Monday through Thursday, between 8:00p.m. to 10:00p.m.

    This Meal Plan also includes $100 in Bonus Bucks that can be used at the FUZ or Benedict's Coffeehouse. Please note that Bonus Bucks do not carry over from each semester, so if you don’t use them, you lose them.

    10 and 5 Meal Plan

    It is the same concept as the 19-meal plan, but you only receive 5 or 10 meals weekly. This plan is only available to students living in apartments with kitchens.

    Commuter Meal Plan

    Ideal for students who are on campus a few days each week, the Commuter Meal Plan offers students blocks of 10 meals for $155. Meals do not expire.

    Special Dietary Needs

    Students with disabilities, who require specialized diets may qualify for accommodations. For more information, please contact the Office of Accessibility Services at adaoffice@saintleo.edu or (352-588-8464).

    Inviting a Guest

    All meal plans will now be able to use their swipes for guests. Guest prices are as follows:

    Breakfast: $15

    Lunch: $16

    Dinner: $17

    Weekend Brunch: $15

    If you are on the 19-meal plan, you can use your Bonus Bucks and/or Lions Loot to pay. Or if you have 5-10- or commuter- meal plans, you can use one of your meal swipes to bring a guest.

    More info: https://www.saintleo.edu/student-experience/on-campus/dining#toc-dining-staff

Stop by FUZ first before you make an unnecessary trip to a store.

Description


Kirk Hall serves as one of the primary administrative buildings on campus - likely to be one of the older and more historically significant buildings on campus. It houses various administrative offices. Kirk Hall also contains classrooms or other multi-purpose spaces that are utilized for various academic and campus activities.



Services


  • Classrooms

    The classroom design prioritizes technology integration and dynamic engagement over conventional layouts. A diverse range of learning modalities has been considered, ensuring that every student benefits from unobstructed visibility of the SMART boards and whiteboards positioned on each wall, regardless of their seating location. Faculty members, equipped with handheld devices, enjoy the freedom to navigate the space without being confined to lecterns or desks. The adaptable seating configurations readily cater to a variety of lesson plans and activities.

Description


Saint Leo Abbey was built in 1883 and is the only Benedictine Church in Florida. It has served as the heart of the university for the students, faculty, staff, monks, and neighboring Catholics. The building is connected to the residence of the Benedictine monks who live on campus and the guest house which is used for private retreats.

Students from all types of backgrounds and faiths are welcome to come and explore and experience our beautiful Abbey and all it has to offer.



More Information


  • The Abbey is open every day of the week from 7:00 a.m. to 8.00 p.m.


  • The Abbey holds Catholic Mass every Sunday at 10:00 a.m. and 7:00 p.m. Daily Mass is also held at the Abbey as well as Confession, Adoration, RCIA, retreats, and Sacraments for new Catholics. Holidays and Holy Days of Obligation are also celebrated here.


  • The art in the Abbey includes Mosaics, Stain Glass Windows, Statues, Wood Carvings, and many other forms of unique and inspiring art.


  • There are Side Altars dedicated to Saint Leo, Saint Boniface, Saint Scholastica, Saint Placidus, Saint Maurus, and the Sacred Heart of Jesus. There are also Holy Relics inside the Church’s walls.

Description


The Saint Leo Abbey Cemetery is the resting place of many nuns, monks, and other notable university figures. The original cemetery begun in 1889 in Dade City was moved to its present location in 1901 near Apartments 3 and 4. Students who live in Apartments 3 and 4 may be able to see the cemetery from their windows or on their walk to their rooms.



More Information


  • The oldest grave in the cemetery is Br. Ambrose Andelfinger’s, who died in 1889.


  • There are several buildings on campus that are named after people buried in the cemetery. How many can you find?


  • According to Lions, Leos, and Learners, a student was once pranked by being put into the cemetery.


  • To find a grave in the cemetery, click here: https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2369602/saint-leo-abbey-cemetery

Description


The St. Jude Chapel is located next to the Student Activities Building (SAB) and across from the SAB Loggia. Students, staff, faculty, and visitors can use the space for their spiritual needs. Inside, there are chairs, holy water, Bibles, prayer books, resources, and more. The sacred Eucharist is also present, making it a Eucharistic chapel.



More Information


  • For convenience, it's open 24/7 and in a central place of prayer on campus, under the clock tower on your way to class. Once a week, after the men's and women's group meetings, students gather to pray night prayer together. Additionally, ashes are distributed from the chapel on Ash Wednesday, and the Palm Sunday procession also starts there. If you have any questions, comments, or concerns, please contact Campus Minister Lucas Norcea at lucas.norcea@saintleo.edu.

Description


The Marion Bowman Center is the ‘home base’ for Saint Leo’s athletic teams. The building has two full basketball and volleyball courts and can seat as many as 1,500 spectators for an event in cushioned, seat-back chairs. The Activities Center houses four classrooms, eight locker rooms, and the athletic department offices.

    The Bowman Center Pool, home to both the men's and women's swim teams, is 25 yards long and holds six lanes. The pool has multiple lifeguard areas, and is connected to both men's and women's locker rooms.
